This was not quite my choice, but the talent pool here in my new home is much more limited, and I am finally embracing the universe's guidance. ❤️

I am still finding my true self, just like Elsa. And I’m working on being like a mother: supportive, compassionate, gentle, loving. Self-judgement when a path doesn’t work out for me is strong, but I know I need to follow my heart as it will tell me where I need to go. 

Character work was completely in line with who I am and I’m still searching for my next journey. I know this door is closing in a few years, at least for the princesses which are my bread and butter, and I’m feeling a bit lost what I want to do next. Which will mean some exploring and false starts. 

It’s so hard to feel like you have room to breathe and figure yourself out in our society where it’s just a struggle to afford to live. I’m a strong believer that this adult generation in the US (especially in states such as California and New York) is not set up for success financially and the institution needs to change. So if you are feeling similarly, you are not a failure. A lot of us can’t sleep because of future worries. Hopefully there is some relief knowing that we are not alone. Which is why being compassionate and motherly towards ourselves is so important. ❤️

When commenting on someone else’s art online…always let your conscience be your guide. ✨✨✨

1. They did not ask for your opinion on the body they did not choose to have. In fact, don’t comment on their body shape or make at all. 

2. Putting down another while complimenting you (or vice versa) is NOT a compliment.

3. Your advice on their makeup, wig, costume is unwanted unless they specifically asked for help. 

4. Creepy solicitations or romantic overtures of any form are up to the discretion of the account holder and may be  blocked at any time without warning. 

5. Think and read before asking. Did they already credit the maker of the item you are curious about in their caption? Have they mentioned them on another post in the same cosplay? Has your question already been answered? 

6. Google translate exists and posting a comment in another language does not make you sneaky or anonymous. Believe me, they see you.

7. Treat others the way you treat another in person. Would you walk up to a random person on the street and call them “ugly” to their face? 

8. You don’t know what a stranger is going through in their life. For a lot of people, social media is a highlight reel and the mental issues they keep private may be seriously impacted by your words. Bullying can have devastating consequences. 

9. Finally, life is not a competition. It’s a collaboration. Many people can be beautiful and talented. Commenting how incredible someone’s art is does not take away from you. Giving love, gives love back to you. So share and comment generously. 💕

Occasionally I have conversations with people about why I hate playing Elsa. Ok, it’s not that I HATE her. She’s an awesome multi layered character who is gorgeous and definitely grew in Frozen 2, but here’s why I’d rather look pretty and just cosplay her 😅: 

1. When Frozen came out, it was like all other characters disappeared for YEARS. There was no variety. Gosh it was boring. 

2. Let It Go is a very hard song to sing at 4 parties a day, especially for a soprano. Parties and working with kids is wearing on the voice at the best of times. 

3. It promoted this weird and ugly favoritism in children. When a kid sidles up to you, looks up at you with big creepy doll eyes and says, “I like you better than Anna,” it uhhh makes you feel real icky inside.

4. Anna is a MUCH better character. And people discount how she was the heart of the movie. The real Elsa would be shy, introverted and uncomfortable at the party. You always kinda have to add a little more personality into her than she actually has to be entertaining, especially on a solo gig. And then you feel like you’ve lost a teeny bit of character integrity.

5. MAKE IT SNOW. It’s funny how no matter how many times you come up with mind blowing improv reasons why you can’t make it snow at the party, the kids always ask again…and again…you become a service representative mindlessly repeating yourself to a dissatisfied customer. 

6. That George Washington hairdo that took the industry like 6 years to make it look decent and still requires caking the makeup on to pull off. You’ve had four different versions of this wig and are never really satisfied. White or blonde or somewhere in between. And then one windy party and POOF!!! Thank goodness for Frozen 2 with the hair down. 

7. Everyone thinks you’re PRINCESS Elsa. QUEEN, ok? Cinderella in a blue dress? Must be Elsa. Brown haired Belle? Totally Elsa.

A few fun(ish?) facts about me: 

1. My first character was Cinderella for someone else's character company. My dad proudly drove me to the gig, we got stuck in traffic, and because I have terrible motion sickness, I threw up on my costume. Fortunately, it was the cheapest of polyester, and was easily rinsed with a water bottle and dried. Yes, I still did the party with several mints. Always leave your problems at the door when performing. 

2. I've cosplayed and done character work since 2012. My current favorite character to perform is Marilyn. My favorite Disney Princess is Rapunzel/Anna. My favorite villain is The Queen. My favorite cosplay is Glinda. 

3. The two biggest loves in my life are my labradoodle, Luke Skybarker, and my fiancé, Brenton. I never thought I would meet my perfect nerdy equal, but I knew the day I met him. And my thoughts are consumed about our LOTR themed wedding in October. 

4. In 2019, after I witnessed a wedding where influencers were as consumed with taking pictures of themselves as the bride, I deleted my account of 100K. I lost quite a few "friends" who, turns out, were not in it to do friendship things, but to get ahead or just make content. I restarted a brand new account in 2020 with MY rules to have fun and be more authentic. It worked. I am now more discerning. 

5. If you wanted to create a trap to catch me it would include: Diet Coke, a couple fantasy paperbacks, tickets to a Broadway show, a BB8 or a BD-1, rhinestones, and a fresh pizza. Ok, just the pizza would work. Or you could play Moon River by Henry Mancini on the piano and I'd willingly enter the trap on the spot. 💕

My mind has been filled with thoughts about the big Strike. I've read the information on the SAG/AFTRA website, I'm listening to others' opinions online...I'm trying to educate myself and formulate my own plan of support. 

Which is really hard since my livelihood depends upon performing the characters from properties of the past that would have possibly been Struck today. But thinking about it, wouldn't almost every production of the past be struck today? That's where it gets tricky. Hollywood has a really ugly history and I'm glad people are taking a stand against its current issues. But, because of my work and all the contractual obligations I already have (into December) with private clients, as well as several collaborations, I need to navigate these waters with careful consideration. 

Here's my personal plan: 

1. I will not be accepting any influencer contracts with studios, attend any premieres (not that I was being invited to these anyways), or promote new or upcoming works in the theaters or tv shows currently airing until the Strike is settled. That unfortunately means no more Barbie for the time being. (Except for 2 upcoming collaborations that were made prior to the onset of the Strike.) 

2. I will complete the current contractual obligations I have, which includes 3 costume collaborations: 1 Barbie, 1 Star Wars, and 1 Batman. And one Barbie party planning collaboration.

3. I will continue to cosplay from past productions that were completed and released prior to the Strike for my character company because it is essential for me to afford to live. Please be gracious and understanding with this. I'm sure you all understand this difficulty and why it is necessary for me to continue this job when I do not have another. 

This came with days of consideration and discussion with my loved ones as to what I can reasonably do to support. Please be kind to influencers and character performers as we are doing the best we can. As a fellow struggling creative, my heart goes to all artists affected by this event and I support the members of SAG/AFTRA strike.

No one will ever be as harsh of a critic as yourself. If you get that nasty abusive voice out of the way, you can open yourself up to do things you never dreamed you were capable of. Putting yourself out there is hard because we are in an age where people can sit behind a screen and be cruel. It can be scary when complete strangers echo your own fears about your art, your body, your talent. We are in a more public society than we have ever been before. It can hurt, but use each experience to inflame your love for what you do and your ambition to try harder. Why should others dictate your destiny? We have a fleeting time here and you get to decide how you spend it yourself. So take those risks even though both internal and external forces are slamming doors, and keep trying. Stop watching and comparing another's journey to yours. Eventually the universe will listen to your passion's insistence and open. And it may be even more surprising and beautiful than you were expecting. ❤️

Did you know I was a hardcore ballet dancer throughout my childhood and teen years? I danced about 5 hours every afternoon, completely destroyed my feet forever (I got custom decorated old lady comfort heels for my wedding), and even tested out of high school so I could travel hours a day to work with my mentor to focus on JUST ballet. And honestly, I might have made it to the corps of some company if I continued to pursue it, but I wasn't genetically gifted with the turnout, extension, and feet to get me far, and it would have been a forever uphill battle. 

All of that said, I LOVE TO DANCE. I'm not a person who has great stamina, but dancing definitely gives me that runner's high feeling. Pure joy.

Being a business owner caused me to become tough. Every now and again I slip into my people-pleasing, don't get mad at me tendencies because I do not like to make waves, but with business professionals I have learned to be direct with my boundaries. As young and female-presenting, I get ignored, belittled, my name conveniently forgotten. Telling someone "no" firmly or what will not work for me is against my nature and it never feels comfortable. It is a joy when I work with someone who values me and treats me with respect. And sometimes I do have to fight for my myself as an artist and small business owner. But I would like to not feel guilty. My next step will be to assert myself and leave the interaction patting myself on the back. And then check my weapons before I come to the dinner table. I would like to compartmentalize that stress into work mode and leave it at the end of the day when it is time to relax. My husband is so good at separating work and home time. But I just love to sharpen my blades continuously in preparation for the next battle. Something I'm working on to alleviate unnecessary emotional stress!
